        title: 'All-or-Nothing Thinking (Black-and-White Thinking)',
        content: `Definition:
Viewing situations on a continuum is difficult. You see things in exactly two categories: perfect or a total failure. If a situation falls short of perfect, you see it as a total failure.

Everyday Examples:
1. "If I don't get an A on this exam, I'm a complete failure."
2. "I ate a piece of cake on my diet, so I totally blew the whole thing."
3. "My presentation wasn't flawless, so I embarrassed myself completely."

How to challenge it:
1. Look for the shades of gray. Ask yourself, "Is this really 100% bad?"
2. Evaluate performance on a scale of 0-100 instead of 0 or 100.
3. Remind yourself that partial success is still success.`,
