        id: 'dist_04',
        category: 'Cognitive Distortions',
        title: 'Disqualifying the Positive',
        content: `Definition:
You reject positive experiences by insisting they "don't count" for some reason or another. In this way, you can maintain a negative belief that is contradicted by your everyday experiences.

Everyday Examples:
1. "They only gave me a compliment because they felt sorry for me."
2. "I did a good job on that project, but anyone could have done it. It was just luck."
3. "My spouse says they love me, but they're just saying that because they're my spouse."

How to challenge it:
1. Say "thank you" to compliments instead of brushing them off.
2. Ask yourself: "If someone else did this, would I dismiss their success?"
3. Recognize that positive experiences are valid data points about your life.`,
