        id: 'dist_06',
        category: 'Cognitive Distortions',
        title: 'Magnification (Catastrophizing) or Minimization',
        content: `Definition:
You exaggerate the importance of things (such as your goof-up or someone else's achievement), or you inappropriately shrink things until they appear tiny (your own desirable qualities or the other fellow's imperfections). Also called the "binocular trick". Catastrophizing involves believing that what happens will be so awful and unbearable that you won't be able to stand it.

Everyday Examples:
1. Magnification: "I made a typo in this email. My boss is going to fire me, and I'll lose my house!"
2. Minimization: "Yes, I got the promotion, but it's not a big deal."
3. Catastrophizing: "If I have a panic attack on the plane, I will absolutely die."

How to challenge it:
1. Decatastrophize: "What is the worst that could happen? What is the best that could happen? What is the most likely thing to happen?"
2. Assess coping ability: "Even if X happens, how would I cope with it?"
3. Reverse the binocular: Magnify your strengths and minimize the scope of the error.`,
